entry.title: Add feature to cancel the effect of MainThreadCompositingPriority when WebRTC is used.
entry.content:
There is strong evidence that MainThreadCompositingPriority causes

audio glitches and video cpu adaptation while in a WebRTC call.

Inspection of traces on Windows and MacOS suggest that the main thread

of the renderer hosting the call competes with other threads that are

critical to the quality of the video call.



Disabling MainThreadCompositingPriority entirely is not an ideal

solution, because it would cause serious regressions to Web Vitals.

This CL creates a feature to disable it only for renderers hosting a

WebRTC call. We'll look into more refined solutions over the next

quarter, but in the meantime, having a simple / low-risk solution that

can be merged to higher channels is important.

entry.title: Revert "[BRP] Remove ref-count-size experiment parameter"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 595f2caa00721cd2797de99a28c910c4fb6330b6.



Reason for revert: Suspected perf regression. Unlikely this is casued

by this CL, as it's supposed to be a no-op, but I wanted to test

the change to fieldtrial_testing_config.json in isolation.



Original change's description:

> [BRP] Remove ref-count-size experiment parameter

>

> Assume everywhere that 0 was passed, which means "use natural size".

> This means use sizeof(PartitionRefCount), possibly adjusted to

> workaround certain issues:

> 1) MTE/BRP race (crbug.com/1445816)

> 2) Mac 13 & 14 crashes (crbug.com/1378822, crbug.com/1457756)

> But this calculation happens internally and is unaffected by this CL.

> The only difference is that we can no longer externally override

> ref_count_size to something higher.

>

> This CL is considered a no-op, since the default param size is

> "natural" (i.e. 0).

>

> Change-Id: Ib5e37e375a0f282cfbb1fa028819dceac0ded0aa

> Reviewed-on: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5148493
